1
00:00:11,702 --> 00:00:14,792
My word and your word will
govern in concert or not at all.

2
00:00:14,873 --> 00:00:16,419
And when I'm not present,

3
00:00:16,499 --> 00:00:18,463
that word shall be
given by my daughter.

4
00:00:18,543 --> 00:00:20,049
They say you are inseparable.

5
00:00:20,129 --> 00:00:22,677
They say he relies upon
you more than any other.

6
00:00:22,757 --> 00:00:24,554
I come on a mission of mercy.

7
00:00:24,634 --> 00:00:26,764
I come on behalf
of Captain Flint.

8
00:00:26,844 --> 00:00:29,308
[GRUNTS]

9
00:00:29,388 --> 00:00:31,644
ROGERS: But if you insist
on making me your villain,

10
00:00:31,724 --> 00:00:33,312
I'll play the part.

11
00:00:33,392 --> 00:00:34,690
From this moment on,

12
00:00:34,770 --> 00:00:37,317
any man participating in
the act of high seas piracy

13
00:00:37,397 --> 00:00:39,278
will be presumed to
be one of your men.

14
00:00:39,358 --> 00:00:41,613
I will catch him
and I will hang him.

15
00:00:41,693 --> 00:00:45,450
Were I you, I might
encourage Governor Rogers

16
00:00:45,530 --> 00:00:47,369
not just to send the gold,

17
00:00:47,449 --> 00:00:49,789
but the man responsible
for stealing it in the first place.

18
00:00:49,869 --> 00:00:52,834
Jack and the cache are to be
moved aboard a secret caravan.

19
00:00:52,914 --> 00:00:55,628
If we can intercept
that caravan,

20
00:00:55,708 --> 00:00:57,547
we can secure both the
money to start our war

21
00:00:57,627 --> 00:00:59,587
and the partner
to help us fight it.

22
00:01:01,047 --> 00:01:03,884
♪

23
00:02:33,396 --> 00:02:34,814
[CLAVICHORD NOTE PLAYS]

24
00:02:38,735 --> 00:02:40,320
[CLAVICHORD NOTE PLAYS]

25
00:02:42,989 --> 00:02:44,617
[CLAVICHORD NOTE PLAYS]

26
00:02:48,871 --> 00:02:50,456
[CLAVICHORD NOTE PLAYS]

27
00:02:57,880 --> 00:02:58,801
[CLAVICHORD NOTE PLAYS]

28
00:02:58,882 --> 00:03:00,092
Please, don't touch that.

29
00:03:13,021 --> 00:03:15,987
VANE: All these things...

30
00:03:16,067 --> 00:03:18,945
porcelain, books...

31
00:03:22,698 --> 00:03:24,617
all so goddamn fragile.

32
00:03:28,872 --> 00:03:31,462
The energy it must
take to maintain it all.

33
00:03:31,542 --> 00:03:32,668
And for what?

34
00:03:34,878 --> 00:03:38,135
I can understand a woman's
desire for domesticity,

35
00:03:38,215 --> 00:03:41,638
but a man's?

36
00:03:41,718 --> 00:03:43,141
That I can't understand.

37
00:03:43,221 --> 00:03:45,974
I can't understand how
you cannot understand.

38
00:03:50,561 --> 00:03:53,484
You have no instinct
towards earning for yourself

39
00:03:53,565 --> 00:03:56,654
a life more comfortable?

40
00:03:56,734 --> 00:03:58,445
I don't.

41
00:04:00,739 --> 00:04:02,953
And had I that instinct,

42
00:04:03,033 --> 00:04:07,666
I would resist it with every
inch of will I could muster.

43
00:04:07,746 --> 00:04:08,959
For that is the single most

44
00:04:09,039 --> 00:04:11,128
dangerous weapon they possess,

45
00:04:12,085 --> 00:04:13,418
the one they tempt.

46
00:04:14,212 --> 00:04:16,134
"Give us your submission,

47
00:04:16,214 --> 00:04:18,925
and we will give you
the comfort you need."

48
00:04:21,761 --> 00:04:26,395
No, I can think of no measure
of comfort worth that price.

49
00:04:26,475 --> 00:04:27,939
[DOOR OPENS]

50
00:04:28,019 --> 00:04:29,941
ANNE: This is taking too long.

51
00:04:30,021 --> 00:04:32,693
No sign of Featherstone's man.

52
00:04:32,773 --> 00:04:33,694
No word on what route

53
00:04:33,774 --> 00:04:35,947
they'll take Jack
across the island.

54
00:04:36,027 --> 00:04:38,991
Word was Jack would
be underway by noon.

55
00:04:39,071 --> 00:04:40,828
If we wait here any longer,

56
00:04:40,908 --> 00:04:41,995
either we're gonna miss him

57
00:04:42,075 --> 00:04:44,123
or someone's gonna
find us hiding out here.

58
00:04:44,203 --> 00:04:47,876
No one will find us because
no one's looking for us.

59
00:04:47,956 --> 00:04:49,503
The war has left the island.

60
00:04:49,583 --> 00:04:51,964
They all saw it happen.

61
00:04:52,044 --> 00:04:53,966
There are at least
half a dozen routes

62
00:04:54,046 --> 00:04:56,678
that Rogers could choose
to send Jack and the cache

63
00:04:56,758 --> 00:04:58,972
to meet the transport
ship on the south coast.

64
00:04:59,052 --> 00:05:00,974
We can't afford to guess wrong.

65
00:05:01,054 --> 00:05:02,600
Can't afford to guess?

66
00:05:02,680 --> 00:05:04,641
We can't afford not to guess.

67
00:05:06,726 --> 00:05:10,484
We miss that caravan,
you lose, what?

68
00:05:10,564 --> 00:05:13,651
Money? Your war?

69
00:05:16,028 --> 00:05:19,660
What I got to lose ain't
something so easy to recover from.

70
00:05:19,740 --> 00:05:23,122
There is no "your loss,"
"his loss," "my loss."

71
00:05:23,202 --> 00:05:25,497
This is not an
either/or proposition.

72
00:05:26,915 --> 00:05:29,004
We're all in this for
our own reasons.

73
00:05:29,084 --> 00:05:31,089
You want your partner
back. He wants victory.

74
00:05:31,169 --> 00:05:33,800
I want to set my home aright.

75
00:05:33,880 --> 00:05:35,969
But we must hold the
line and stand together.

76
00:05:36,049 --> 00:05:37,971
We must.

77
00:05:38,051 --> 00:05:39,637
There's simply no alternative.

78
00:05:41,722 --> 00:05:43,102
There's a rider approaching.

79
00:05:43,182 --> 00:05:45,977
Is it Featherstone's
man? It is. Here he comes.

80
00:05:57,114 --> 00:06:00,117
[MEN SHOUTING]
[DRUMS BEATING]

81
00:06:04,371 --> 00:06:06,081
That's for you.

82
00:06:08,376 --> 00:06:11,966
Consider that your share.

83
00:06:12,046 --> 00:06:13,256
For the company.

84
00:06:15,216 --> 00:06:18,139
I suspect I'll be
leaving shortly.

85
00:06:18,219 --> 00:06:21,806
Don't despair. Some other poor
bastard'll take my place soon enough.

86
00:06:23,392 --> 00:06:25,147
I wish I could assure you

87
00:06:25,227 --> 00:06:28,230
that he would be as
generous as I with his scraps.

88
00:06:31,734 --> 00:06:33,322
Either way, you mustn't settle

89
00:06:33,402 --> 00:06:37,160
for whatever refuse
finds its way into this cell.

90
00:06:37,240 --> 00:06:39,120
There's a whole world out there

91
00:06:39,200 --> 00:06:42,916
that every so often
rewards ambition.

92
00:06:42,996 --> 00:06:45,707
Mark my words.

93
00:06:46,916 --> 00:06:49,961
Today the crumbs,
tomorrow the loaf.

94
00:06:52,256 --> 00:06:54,633
Perhaps someday the
whole damn boulangerie.

95
00:06:59,221 --> 00:07:00,685
You're welcome.

96
00:07:00,765 --> 00:07:03,062
[LOCK RATTLING]

97
00:07:03,142 --> 00:07:04,063
[SQUEAKS]

98
00:07:04,143 --> 00:07:05,811
[DOOR OPENS]

99
00:07:08,065 --> 00:07:10,942
[SEAGULL SQUAWKING]

100
00:07:13,195 --> 00:07:16,156
[HORSES WHICKERING]

101
00:07:24,082 --> 00:07:26,129
[CHATTERING]

102
00:07:26,209 --> 00:07:28,753
♪

103
00:07:36,136 --> 00:07:38,138
MAN: Be careful of
the ammunition cases.

104
00:07:49,734 --> 00:07:53,321
Anne exchanged the
cache for my release.

105
00:07:54,906 --> 00:07:55,824
Yes.

106
00:07:58,910 --> 00:08:01,124
This does not
seem like a release.

107
00:08:01,204 --> 00:08:05,838
Spain has demanded I deliver
you along with the cache.

108
00:08:05,918 --> 00:08:08,257
I am told that once you and
the cache arrive at Havana,

109
00:08:08,337 --> 00:08:11,093
my debt to Spain will be repaid.

110
00:08:11,173 --> 00:08:13,763
I did not appreciate having terms
altered after the fact in this way,

111
00:08:13,843 --> 00:08:18,225
but in this moment I am simply
in no position to refuse them.

112
00:08:18,305 --> 00:08:20,270
I see.

113
00:08:20,350 --> 00:08:21,313
Perhaps you were right,

114
00:08:21,393 --> 00:08:22,981
that in a place like this

115
00:08:23,061 --> 00:08:25,981
there is no progress
without awful sacrifice.

116
00:08:27,399 --> 00:08:28,904
- Make ready to depart.
- MAN: Yes, sir!

117
00:08:28,984 --> 00:08:30,655
[HORSE WHINNIES]

118
00:08:30,735 --> 00:08:32,991
If it's any consolation,

119
00:08:33,071 --> 00:08:35,828
no harm was done
to your partner.

120
00:08:35,908 --> 00:08:39,290
She left the
transaction unscathed.

121
00:08:39,370 --> 00:08:40,291
Ready, my lord.

122
00:08:40,371 --> 00:08:41,456
Let's go.

123
00:08:44,250 --> 00:08:45,296
So she's alive? Anne?

124
00:08:45,376 --> 00:08:46,297
MAN: Prepare to mount up!

125
00:08:46,377 --> 00:08:49,298
She is. You have my word.

126
00:08:54,553 --> 00:08:57,806
Hup! Hup! Hup! [WHINNIES]

127
00:09:24,877 --> 00:09:27,338
[WIND WHISTLING]

128
00:09:31,426 --> 00:09:33,306
MADI: So we are
able to see the island,

129
00:09:33,386 --> 00:09:35,016
but the island cannot see us.

130
00:09:35,096 --> 00:09:37,853
How is this possible?

131
00:09:37,933 --> 00:09:41,314
Well, Mr. De Groot says
that from this position,

132
00:09:41,394 --> 00:09:42,441
when viewed from the beach,

133
00:09:42,521 --> 00:09:45,193
our hull sits
beneath the horizon

134
00:09:45,273 --> 00:09:46,863
while our masts are above it.

135
00:09:46,943 --> 00:09:48,030
Now, with the sails furled,

136
00:09:48,110 --> 00:09:50,199
the masts are too
thin to be seen.

137
00:09:50,279 --> 00:09:53,035
Thus, our lookout has
a view of the beach,

138
00:09:53,115 --> 00:09:57,373
but the beach has
no view of him or us.

139
00:09:57,453 --> 00:09:59,834
It's a neat trick, I must say.

140
00:09:59,914 --> 00:10:01,545
How does one
determine this position,

141
00:10:01,625 --> 00:10:05,299
one in which we exist and
don't exist at the same time?

142
00:10:05,379 --> 00:10:09,344
One waits for Mr. De
Groot to finish speaking,

143
00:10:09,424 --> 00:10:11,346
frowns thoughtfully,

144
00:10:11,426 --> 00:10:15,059
and then repeats phonetically
what he said to the men.

145
00:10:15,139 --> 00:10:17,187
[CHUCKLES] A few months ago,

146
00:10:17,267 --> 00:10:19,355
all they let me do
on this ship was cook.

147
00:10:19,435 --> 00:10:21,316
I'm learning as fast as I can.

148
00:10:21,396 --> 00:10:23,026
Clearly.

149
00:10:23,106 --> 00:10:25,361
Yes, something less
than confidence-inspiring

150
00:10:25,441 --> 00:10:27,363
for the men, I would think,

151
00:10:27,443 --> 00:10:30,489
were I to admit the depths of
my ignorance on the subject.

152
00:10:32,366 --> 00:10:34,330
What the men think of you...

153
00:10:34,410 --> 00:10:36,999
your men and my men...

154
00:10:37,079 --> 00:10:38,542
would seem to be
evolving as we speak.

155
00:10:38,622 --> 00:10:40,499
Ah, yes.

156
00:10:44,254 --> 00:10:47,302
The story about what
happened last night

157
00:10:47,382 --> 00:10:48,845
has been retold as many times

158
00:10:48,925 --> 00:10:50,385
as there are men on this ship.

159
00:10:53,263 --> 00:10:55,477
You expressed your concern to me

160
00:10:55,557 --> 00:10:58,313
that to truly partner
with your captain,

161
00:10:58,393 --> 00:11:01,188
you would need to join
him down a dark path.

162
00:11:03,107 --> 00:11:04,320
And that you fear it...

163
00:11:04,400 --> 00:11:05,988
it might lead you to a place

164
00:11:06,068 --> 00:11:07,945
you would not be
able to return from.

165
00:11:11,365 --> 00:11:13,201
You're concerned about me.

166
00:11:15,412 --> 00:11:17,167
The alliance between your crew

167
00:11:17,247 --> 00:11:18,999
and my people is critical.

168
00:11:20,917 --> 00:11:23,173
Without it, we are all nowhere.

169
00:11:23,253 --> 00:11:25,008
If your mind is not clear

170
00:11:25,088 --> 00:11:27,010
and the alliance cannot hold,

171
00:11:27,090 --> 00:11:29,847
all will be lost.

172
00:11:29,927 --> 00:11:33,640
So, yes, I am concerned.

173
00:11:35,558 --> 00:11:37,060
Hmm. Yes.

174
00:11:38,936 --> 00:11:40,650
Last night was not an experience

175
00:11:40,730 --> 00:11:43,317
I hope to repeat anytime soon.

176
00:11:45,569 --> 00:11:47,321
But my mind is clear.

177
00:11:48,739 --> 00:11:50,286
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

178
00:11:50,366 --> 00:11:53,163
Mr. Silver, I need
to speak with you.

179
00:11:53,243 --> 00:11:54,244
Alone, please.

180
00:11:57,582 --> 00:12:00,627
[CREW CHATTERING]

181
00:12:21,607 --> 00:12:22,983
What the fuck happened?

182
00:12:25,736 --> 00:12:29,369
In that... camp,

183
00:12:29,449 --> 00:12:31,204
they killed Parker.

184
00:12:31,284 --> 00:12:33,040
They killed Louis.

185
00:12:33,120 --> 00:12:37,544
They killed Graves
and they killed Simon.

186
00:12:37,624 --> 00:12:40,461
They chose them from among
us to be tortured and killed.

187
00:12:42,130 --> 00:12:44,424
And that one was the
one doing the choosing.

188
00:12:53,474 --> 00:12:57,604
[MOANING AND GASPING]

189
00:13:01,108 --> 00:13:04,406
[GASPING]

190
00:13:04,486 --> 00:13:07,993
[GASPING CONTINUES]

191
00:13:08,073 --> 00:13:13,667
[GASPING]

192
00:13:13,747 --> 00:13:17,542
[PANTING]

193
00:13:25,593 --> 00:13:27,640
What is it you're hiding from?

194
00:13:27,720 --> 00:13:31,185
Excuse me?

195
00:13:31,265 --> 00:13:34,563
I only meant I know
you must be very busy,

196
00:13:34,643 --> 00:13:38,192
what with your responsibilities.

197
00:13:38,272 --> 00:13:40,529
But to still be here
so late in the morning,

198
00:13:40,609 --> 00:13:42,611
I assume there's
something you're avoiding.

199
00:13:46,281 --> 00:13:48,495
For what it's worth,

200
00:13:48,575 --> 00:13:52,457
I believe the madam chose
me for you because I am new.

201
00:13:52,537 --> 00:13:56,671
I have no notions about
what you once were.

202
00:13:56,751 --> 00:13:59,173
No motive to gossip.

203
00:13:59,253 --> 00:14:00,508
Georgia.

204
00:14:00,588 --> 00:14:03,636
Yes?

205
00:14:03,716 --> 00:14:06,347
I know the games.

206
00:14:06,427 --> 00:14:07,805
I have played them all.

207
00:14:10,265 --> 00:14:13,021
If you ever wish to
be in my bed again,

208
00:14:13,101 --> 00:14:17,025
that is the last one you
will ever play with me.

209
00:14:17,105 --> 00:14:18,694
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

210
00:14:18,774 --> 00:14:19,945
Yes?

211
00:14:20,025 --> 00:14:21,655
WOMAN: Miss
Guthrie's downstairs.

212
00:14:21,735 --> 00:14:23,363
She's asking for you.

213
00:14:26,616 --> 00:14:29,828
[CHATTER AND LAUGHTER]

214
00:14:31,579 --> 00:14:32,622
[PARROT SQUAWKS]

215
00:14:34,582 --> 00:14:35,792
[PARROT SQUAWKS]

216
00:14:38,754 --> 00:14:40,297
Yes?

217
00:14:43,425 --> 00:14:44,677
What happened?

218
00:14:45,761 --> 00:14:48,684
The cache is in our possession.

219
00:14:48,764 --> 00:14:49,685
It's on its way as we speak

220
00:14:49,765 --> 00:14:51,855
to the transport
and then to Havana.

221
00:14:51,935 --> 00:14:53,857
With Jack.

222
00:14:53,937 --> 00:14:55,192
Yes.

223
00:14:55,272 --> 00:14:57,194
The governor is
seeing to it personally

224
00:14:57,274 --> 00:15:00,530
that the transport
sets sail with its cargo.

225
00:15:00,610 --> 00:15:01,531
Within a matter of hours,

226
00:15:01,611 --> 00:15:02,657
the Spanish issue will be closed

227
00:15:02,737 --> 00:15:04,656
and we will be free
to move forward.

228
00:15:06,742 --> 00:15:07,785
And Anne?

229
00:15:09,787 --> 00:15:11,459
The men said she was angered.

230
00:15:11,539 --> 00:15:14,378
When she realized
that Jack wasn't there,

231
00:15:14,458 --> 00:15:15,880
she let the cache go.

232
00:15:15,960 --> 00:15:18,504
Anne was unharmed.

233
00:15:21,300 --> 00:15:24,389
Unharmed? Yes.

234
00:15:24,469 --> 00:15:26,558
I advised the governor to
send eight men to the exchange

235
00:15:26,638 --> 00:15:28,101
to deter any attempt
on her part to fight...

236
00:15:28,181 --> 00:15:30,395
When did she realize?

237
00:15:30,475 --> 00:15:32,731
I'm sorry?

238
00:15:32,811 --> 00:15:34,691
That Jack was not there.

239
00:15:34,772 --> 00:15:37,654
When did Anne realize
that she had been lied to?

240
00:15:37,734 --> 00:15:40,240
Was it before or after
they secured the cache?

241
00:15:40,320 --> 00:15:43,323
Before, I think. Why?

242
00:15:45,742 --> 00:15:47,205
When you told me this was to be,

243
00:15:47,285 --> 00:15:50,709
I was upset by the thought
of having lied to Anne.

244
00:15:50,789 --> 00:15:52,378
I was devastated
by the certainty

245
00:15:52,458 --> 00:15:55,256
it would unavoidably
lead to her death.

246
00:15:55,336 --> 00:15:58,843
For the moment she realized
that Jack was not there,

247
00:15:58,923 --> 00:16:00,594
that she had been crossed

248
00:16:00,674 --> 00:16:02,680
and that she would
likely never see him again,

249
00:16:02,760 --> 00:16:04,850
she would attempt to kill anyone

250
00:16:04,930 --> 00:16:06,810
she deemed responsible.

251
00:16:06,890 --> 00:16:09,437
Eight?

252
00:16:09,517 --> 00:16:11,648
You could have
sent a thousand men.

253
00:16:11,728 --> 00:16:13,650
It would not have deterred her.

254
00:16:13,730 --> 00:16:14,818
And now you are saying to me

255
00:16:14,898 --> 00:16:16,820
that she knew she
had been crossed

256
00:16:16,900 --> 00:16:20,321
and chose to walk
away to save herself?

257
00:16:23,449 --> 00:16:24,867
[HORSE WHINNIES]

258
00:16:40,300 --> 00:16:41,551
Do you speak Spanish?

259
00:16:43,053 --> 00:16:43,974
Beg pardon?

260
00:16:44,054 --> 00:16:46,390
¿Habla español?

261
00:16:47,934 --> 00:16:49,522
A little.

262
00:16:49,602 --> 00:16:51,357
You? Hardly at all.

263
00:16:51,437 --> 00:16:53,693
If I'm in Havana
in a day or two,

264
00:16:53,773 --> 00:16:56,362
I assume I'll be
hearing a lot of it...

265
00:16:56,442 --> 00:16:59,198
shouted by bitter old
women in a crowd,

266
00:16:59,278 --> 00:17:03,370
growled by angry officials.

267
00:17:03,450 --> 00:17:06,832
It seems a rotten thing
to wish upon anyone,

268
00:17:06,912 --> 00:17:11,795
an unflattering eulogy
in an unfamiliar town.

269
00:17:11,875 --> 00:17:12,963
It'll be quick,

270
00:17:13,043 --> 00:17:15,841
to whatever extent it
sets your mind at ease.

271
00:17:15,921 --> 00:17:17,844
The gold is theirs.

272
00:17:17,924 --> 00:17:19,846
The gems are theirs.

273
00:17:19,926 --> 00:17:21,681
They don't need anything
from you anymore,

274
00:17:21,761 --> 00:17:22,933
and as such
they're likely to want

275
00:17:23,013 --> 00:17:26,808
to put the entire affair
behind them and move on.

276
00:17:29,602 --> 00:17:31,442
I'm sorry. "If"?

277
00:17:31,522 --> 00:17:33,611
Beg pardon?

278
00:17:33,691 --> 00:17:36,697
You said, "If I'm in Havana."

279
00:17:36,777 --> 00:17:38,612
In your mind this
outcome is still in doubt.

280
00:17:40,448 --> 00:17:46,041
Well, the odds are
certainly in its favor,

281
00:17:46,121 --> 00:17:48,794
but it is by no
means a certainty.

282
00:17:48,874 --> 00:17:51,713
How so exactly?

283
00:17:51,793 --> 00:17:53,840
You said Anne is
alive, did you not?

284
00:17:53,920 --> 00:17:55,884
I would argue as
long as that is true,

285
00:17:55,964 --> 00:17:58,387
there's a chance,
however remote,

286
00:17:58,467 --> 00:17:59,888
that she will
frustrate your efforts

287
00:17:59,968 --> 00:18:01,557
to send me off to my death.

288
00:18:01,637 --> 00:18:03,017
Out of curiosity,

289
00:18:03,097 --> 00:18:04,519
how would she go
about doing that?

290
00:18:04,599 --> 00:18:05,808
Well, I have no idea.

291
00:18:07,977 --> 00:18:09,732
Everything and anything
in her power, I imagine,

292
00:18:09,812 --> 00:18:10,858
up to and including walking out

293
00:18:10,938 --> 00:18:12,735
in the middle of
the road ahead of us

294
00:18:12,815 --> 00:18:14,195
to be run over by your horses

295
00:18:14,275 --> 00:18:17,654
in the hope of slowing you
down for even a moment.

296
00:18:20,949 --> 00:18:23,706
It is fascinating to me

297
00:18:23,786 --> 00:18:25,541
how stubbornly you people expect

298
00:18:25,621 --> 00:18:28,919
the unlikeliest of outcomes
because you prefer them.

299
00:18:28,999 --> 00:18:31,548
You expect the world to
become what you want it to be

300
00:18:31,628 --> 00:18:34,968
despite all available evidence
and experience to the contrary.

301
00:18:35,048 --> 00:18:39,889
This was not the way I'd
hoped this affair would play out.

302
00:18:39,969 --> 00:18:41,099
But I can assure you

303
00:18:41,179 --> 00:18:42,017
it is most certainly
not going to play out

304
00:18:42,097 --> 00:18:44,562
the way you hope it will either,

305
00:18:44,642 --> 00:18:47,023
because even to stand
in the road ahead of us,

306
00:18:47,103 --> 00:18:49,358
she would have to know
which road to stand in.

307
00:18:49,438 --> 00:18:51,944
You held the route secret.

308
00:18:52,024 --> 00:18:54,572
I held a number of
potential routes secret

309
00:18:54,652 --> 00:18:57,533
before settling upon this one

310
00:18:57,613 --> 00:18:59,870
so that even if the
secrets were compromised,

311
00:18:59,950 --> 00:19:02,372
anyone intending to hit us
would be more than likely

312
00:19:02,452 --> 00:19:05,872
in possession of
the wrong route.

313
00:19:15,007 --> 00:19:18,014
CHAMBERLAIN: Let me
be sure I have this right.

314
00:19:18,094 --> 00:19:20,725
So the plan to recover
the stolen cache of gems...

315
00:19:20,805 --> 00:19:23,019
your plan to recover
the stolen cache of gems

316
00:19:23,099 --> 00:19:25,980
has worked in exactly the
manner you suggested it would.

317
00:19:26,060 --> 00:19:28,984
Only now you believe
this is a bad thing...

318
00:19:29,064 --> 00:19:30,986
evidence of a plan to
rescue Mr. Rackham

319
00:19:31,066 --> 00:19:34,364
and once again recover
the cache of gems.

320
00:19:34,444 --> 00:19:35,824
That is what you're
suggesting, yes?

321
00:19:35,904 --> 00:19:38,035
I can understand why
this may be hard to believe,

322
00:19:38,115 --> 00:19:39,703
but I know Anne
Bonny well enough

323
00:19:39,783 --> 00:19:42,874
to know that it is a certainty
something here is amiss.

324
00:19:42,954 --> 00:19:44,709
That her behavior
should coincide

325
00:19:44,789 --> 00:19:46,377
with the presence of
Captain Flint on the island

326
00:19:46,457 --> 00:19:47,879
only hours before

327
00:19:47,959 --> 00:19:49,631
most certainly points to
a plot being underway.

328
00:19:49,711 --> 00:19:51,382
I beg your pardon.

329
00:19:51,462 --> 00:19:53,718
So now Captain Flint is
somehow involved in this plot

330
00:19:53,798 --> 00:19:56,388
despite the fact that his
ship left the island hours ago?

331
00:19:56,468 --> 00:20:00,017
And I am to redeploy men into
the interior away from Nassau Town,

332
00:20:00,097 --> 00:20:01,894
leaving their
positions undefended?

333
00:20:01,974 --> 00:20:03,020
I'm sorry, are you suggesting

334
00:20:03,100 --> 00:20:05,022
there's some
ulterior motive here?

335
00:20:05,102 --> 00:20:07,525
I'm suggesting that simply
because the governor

336
00:20:07,605 --> 00:20:10,528
decided to put
his... trust in you,

337
00:20:10,608 --> 00:20:12,739
I have no intention
of doing the same.

338
00:20:12,819 --> 00:20:13,865
The situation is well in hand.

339
00:20:13,945 --> 00:20:14,950
Thank you for your concern.

340
00:20:15,030 --> 00:20:16,651
Well in hand?

341
00:20:16,824 --> 00:20:17,994
I'm telling you the
situation is potentially

342
00:20:18,074 --> 00:20:19,704
about to get
entirely out of hand.

343
00:20:19,784 --> 00:20:21,119
You're not fucking hearing me.

344
00:20:23,788 --> 00:20:27,046
Even if somebody wanted to
move against the governor's caravan,

345
00:20:27,126 --> 00:20:30,049
they wouldn't know where
to find the governor's caravan.

346
00:20:30,129 --> 00:20:31,551
The route was
altered multiple times.

347
00:20:31,631 --> 00:20:32,802
False schedules
were distributed.

348
00:20:32,882 --> 00:20:34,220
Nobody knows exactly
when they were set to leave.

349
00:20:34,300 --> 00:20:36,180
Nobody knows what route
they finally decided upon.

350
00:20:36,260 --> 00:20:39,183
- Nobody knows who...
- MAX: I know.

351
00:20:39,263 --> 00:20:40,561
I know the route.

352
00:20:40,641 --> 00:20:42,896
A boy in my employ saw scouts

353
00:20:42,976 --> 00:20:44,940
on the west trail
road late last night.

354
00:20:45,020 --> 00:20:47,522
That is it, is it not?

355
00:20:49,650 --> 00:20:51,196
I am assuming you
did not send men

356
00:20:51,276 --> 00:20:52,861
to scout the decoy routes?

357
00:20:54,989 --> 00:20:57,787
Did you tell anyone what
your boy has told you?

358
00:20:57,867 --> 00:21:00,206
No. And would your boy

359
00:21:00,286 --> 00:21:03,042
sell his information
without your knowledge?

360
00:21:03,122 --> 00:21:06,087
No. Good.

361
00:21:06,167 --> 00:21:08,047
Then we have nothing
to fucking worry about.

362
00:21:08,127 --> 00:21:09,129
Ladies.

363
00:21:17,012 --> 00:21:20,015
[CROWD CHATTERING]

364
00:21:23,979 --> 00:21:25,984
Fuck your pride.

365
00:21:26,064 --> 00:21:28,028
If I can swallow mine
to be standing here,

366
00:21:28,108 --> 00:21:30,026
you'll do the same to listen.

367
00:21:33,280 --> 00:21:35,076
Because if you
and I can't figure out

368
00:21:35,156 --> 00:21:37,037
a way to work
together in this moment,

369
00:21:37,117 --> 00:21:39,120
everything may be lost.

370
00:21:43,124 --> 00:21:45,004
How many people know about this?

371
00:21:45,084 --> 00:21:47,882
No one outside that room.

372
00:21:47,962 --> 00:21:48,883
In less than an hour,

373
00:21:48,963 --> 00:21:50,885
I need to move
this ship to the coast

374
00:21:50,965 --> 00:21:53,555
to retrieve our captain
and a fortune in gems

375
00:21:53,635 --> 00:21:56,892
upon which the lives of well
over a thousand people depend.

376
00:21:56,972 --> 00:21:58,727
Now that is all
going up in smoke

377
00:21:58,807 --> 00:22:01,685
because Mr. Dobbs
cannot control his anger.

378
00:22:03,270 --> 00:22:06,193
It don't have to.

379
00:22:06,273 --> 00:22:08,196
No.

380
00:22:08,276 --> 00:22:09,739
If we let him leave that room,

381
00:22:09,819 --> 00:22:10,990
he's going to tell his
men what happened

382
00:22:11,070 --> 00:22:12,075
and we're going to
have a war on our hands.

383
00:22:12,155 --> 00:22:13,576
I understand that,

384
00:22:13,656 --> 00:22:14,661
but the answer
is not going to be

385
00:22:14,741 --> 00:22:15,954
finishing what Dobbs started

386
00:22:16,034 --> 00:22:17,076
and murdering that man.

387
00:22:19,245 --> 00:22:20,875
[SIGHS]

388
00:22:20,955 --> 00:22:23,045
All right.

389
00:22:23,125 --> 00:22:24,880
Then we put a knife in his hands

390
00:22:24,960 --> 00:22:27,049
and we let him even the score.

391
00:22:27,129 --> 00:22:28,717
For reasons passing
understanding,

392
00:22:28,797 --> 00:22:31,220
Mr. Dobbs still has a
number of friends on this crew.

393
00:22:31,300 --> 00:22:33,052
How do we explain his
disappearance to them?

394
00:22:35,971 --> 00:22:38,561
This story is getting out,

395
00:22:38,641 --> 00:22:41,102
and when it does, all hell
is going to break loose.

396
00:22:43,271 --> 00:22:45,106
Then what do we do?

397
00:23:07,964 --> 00:23:09,886
This is the man responsible.

398
00:23:09,966 --> 00:23:11,885
He's the only man responsible.

399
00:23:14,304 --> 00:23:17,602
I suggest you and I address
the combined crew together.

400
00:23:17,682 --> 00:23:21,399
This man will be held
to account and punished

401
00:23:21,479 --> 00:23:23,356
swiftly and severely.

402
00:23:43,001 --> 00:23:44,253
[WHIMPERS]

403
00:23:54,347 --> 00:23:55,849
May I have a knife, please?

404
00:24:03,148 --> 00:24:04,692
[KNIFE SLIDES FROM SCABBARD]

405
00:24:31,803 --> 00:24:33,890
[ROPE SLICING]

406
00:24:49,323 --> 00:24:50,365
Wait a minute. Hold on.

407
00:24:52,451 --> 00:24:54,748
Until I know what
he's going to say,

408
00:24:54,828 --> 00:24:57,209
I can't let anyone
walk out of here.

409
00:24:57,289 --> 00:24:59,253
He isn't going to say anything.

410
00:24:59,333 --> 00:25:00,459
He has to say something.

411
00:25:02,462 --> 00:25:06,219
He's going to say that he
spoke impertinently to me,

412
00:25:06,299 --> 00:25:08,054
Kofi took offense,

413
00:25:08,134 --> 00:25:10,345
and it will not be
spoken of again.

414
00:25:11,804 --> 00:25:13,726
Just like that.

415
00:25:13,806 --> 00:25:16,059
Yes. Now let him go.

416
00:25:21,440 --> 00:25:23,776
♪

417
00:25:31,826 --> 00:25:33,081
If he says a word...

418
00:25:33,161 --> 00:25:37,002
When I speak, my men listen,

419
00:25:37,082 --> 00:25:38,542
and they do as I say.

420
00:25:52,306 --> 00:25:55,229
[CHATTERING]

421
00:25:55,309 --> 00:25:58,232
A secret caravan to move
Rackham to a secret transport,

422
00:25:58,312 --> 00:25:59,943
and no one knows
about this but you.

423
00:26:00,023 --> 00:26:02,404
Me, the governor, his cabinet,

424
00:26:02,484 --> 00:26:05,407
eight dragoons, their
quartermaster, the carriage driver...

425
00:26:05,487 --> 00:26:06,947
plenty of people know
about it, just not you.

426
00:26:09,491 --> 00:26:11,205
And you believe
there's a plot underway

427
00:26:11,285 --> 00:26:12,873
to attack this secret caravan...

428
00:26:12,953 --> 00:26:15,543
a plot that somehow
involves Captain Flint,

429
00:26:15,623 --> 00:26:18,796
whom everyone saw sail
into open water hours ago.

430
00:26:18,876 --> 00:26:21,382
Jesus! Chamberlain
can ignore this.

431
00:26:21,462 --> 00:26:24,928
He doesn't know me, he doesn't
know Bonny, he doesn't know Flint.

432
00:26:25,008 --> 00:26:28,556
Now, if it turns out that I'm right
about this, he'll look like a fool,

433
00:26:28,636 --> 00:26:30,976
but at least his ignorance of the
players involved will be some defense.

434
00:26:31,056 --> 00:26:32,561
If you choose to ignore me,

435
00:26:32,641 --> 00:26:35,397
it will be far harder for
you to find an excuse.

436
00:26:35,477 --> 00:26:39,109
I watched it depart, the Walrus.

437
00:26:39,189 --> 00:26:41,278
Had a man with a glass
watching her set sail,

438
00:26:41,358 --> 00:26:43,322
watching her clear the
horizon and disappear...

439
00:26:43,403 --> 00:26:44,866
Do you know what? I
don't have time for this.

440
00:26:44,946 --> 00:26:47,198
...except for
the glints of light.

441
00:26:50,201 --> 00:26:51,122
What?

442
00:26:51,202 --> 00:26:52,916
I had my man keep his glass

443
00:26:52,996 --> 00:26:53,917
to the spot on the horizon

444
00:26:53,997 --> 00:26:56,086
where the Walrus disappeared.

445
00:26:56,166 --> 00:26:57,379
And roughly every 15 minutes,

446
00:26:57,459 --> 00:26:59,090
he reported
seeing glints of light

447
00:26:59,170 --> 00:27:00,466
from her last position.

448
00:27:00,546 --> 00:27:02,552
What the fuck does that mean?

449
00:27:02,632 --> 00:27:04,929
Oh, it could mean nothing.

450
00:27:05,009 --> 00:27:07,890
Random artifact of
sunlight off the water.

451
00:27:07,970 --> 00:27:13,105
Or it could be the reflection of a
spyglass upon one of her masts...

452
00:27:13,185 --> 00:27:14,439
the ship beneath bare poles,

453
00:27:14,519 --> 00:27:18,231
waiting silently, invisibly,
for a signal to return.

454
00:27:20,317 --> 00:27:21,405
I beat him,

455
00:27:21,485 --> 00:27:23,073
and then I watched
him return from the dead

456
00:27:23,153 --> 00:27:25,909
to negate my victory,

457
00:27:25,989 --> 00:27:27,412
to watch his partner murder mine

458
00:27:27,492 --> 00:27:30,415
and aggravate the affront.

459
00:27:30,495 --> 00:27:32,083
You and I have our history,

460
00:27:32,163 --> 00:27:33,918
but Flint and I have
unfinished business

461
00:27:33,998 --> 00:27:36,250
of a far more serious sort.

462
00:27:39,337 --> 00:27:41,924
[HORSE NEIGHS]

463
00:27:47,638 --> 00:27:50,933
My father was a tailor in Leeds.

464
00:27:54,478 --> 00:27:56,526
As was his father

465
00:27:56,606 --> 00:27:59,070
and his father's father.

466
00:27:59,150 --> 00:28:01,406
Time was if a man
on the Avondale Road

467
00:28:01,486 --> 00:28:03,533
asked where he might find the
finest clothes in northern England,

468
00:28:03,613 --> 00:28:06,202
he was pointed toward the
shop of a man named Rackham.

469
00:28:06,282 --> 00:28:09,080
Then the men who sell wool

470
00:28:09,160 --> 00:28:10,415
decide they'd
prefer not to compete

471
00:28:10,495 --> 00:28:12,209
with the men who
imported fine cotton.

472
00:28:12,289 --> 00:28:13,544
And as the men who sell wool

473
00:28:13,624 --> 00:28:16,547
have the ears of the
men who make laws,

474
00:28:16,627 --> 00:28:20,092
an embargo is enacted
to increase profits

475
00:28:20,172 --> 00:28:21,677
and calico disappears.

476
00:28:21,757 --> 00:28:24,096
And my father's business

477
00:28:24,176 --> 00:28:26,558
that he inherited
from his father

478
00:28:26,638 --> 00:28:27,601
and his father's father

479
00:28:27,681 --> 00:28:30,392
begins to wither and die.

480
00:28:32,477 --> 00:28:36,068
And my father suffers the
compound shame of financial failure

481
00:28:36,148 --> 00:28:39,237
seen through the eyes of his son

482
00:28:39,317 --> 00:28:41,237
and descended into drink.

483
00:28:43,322 --> 00:28:46,079
I'd sit beside him as a
boy at the Sunday service

484
00:28:46,159 --> 00:28:50,583
as he shouted at the
pastor, at the altar...

485
00:28:50,663 --> 00:28:51,751
at anyone who'd
listen, really...

486
00:28:51,831 --> 00:28:54,755
at the injustice of it all.

487
00:28:54,835 --> 00:28:59,426
And I'd put my arm over his
shoulder as the insults began,

488
00:28:59,506 --> 00:29:01,095
help carry him
out of the church.

489
00:29:01,175 --> 00:29:03,177
God, the insults.

490
00:29:04,636 --> 00:29:07,101
At his funeral, our
neighbors were kind enough

491
00:29:07,181 --> 00:29:10,271
to whisper them rather
than call them out loud.

492
00:29:10,351 --> 00:29:12,440
So, I set to work,

493
00:29:12,520 --> 00:29:15,443
determined to rebuild
what had been taken away.

494
00:29:15,523 --> 00:29:17,525
I was 13 years old.
but I was determined...

495
00:29:19,819 --> 00:29:22,575
...until a man
arrived at my door

496
00:29:22,655 --> 00:29:26,122
claiming to hold debts
belonging to my father.

497
00:29:26,202 --> 00:29:28,124
Debts accumulated
as my father drank.

498
00:29:28,204 --> 00:29:31,293
Debts he claimed that
now belonged to me.

499
00:29:31,373 --> 00:29:35,089
Debts I could not possibly
have hoped to repay.

500
00:29:35,169 --> 00:29:38,427
Debts over which this man
would have seen me imprisoned...

501
00:29:38,507 --> 00:29:40,721
imprisoned in a place where the
debts would have been discharged

502
00:29:40,801 --> 00:29:42,723
only through hard labor.

503
00:29:42,803 --> 00:29:45,726
Hard labor with no
wages, working at...

504
00:29:45,806 --> 00:29:48,103
wait for it...

505
00:29:48,183 --> 00:29:51,061
the production of textiles.

506
00:29:55,691 --> 00:30:01,367
"You people, incapable of
accepting the world as it is,"

507
00:30:01,447 --> 00:30:04,742
says the man to whom the
world handed everything.

508
00:30:06,619 --> 00:30:08,709
If no Anne, if no rescue,

509
00:30:08,789 --> 00:30:11,420
if this is defeat for
me, then know this.

510
00:30:11,500 --> 00:30:15,424
You and I were neck and
neck in this race right till the end.

511
00:30:15,504 --> 00:30:20,596
But, Jesus, did I make up
a lot of ground to catch you.

512
00:30:20,676 --> 00:30:23,433
You think the world's
been that kind to me?

513
00:30:23,513 --> 00:30:25,518
That I'm that much
softer than you?

514
00:30:25,598 --> 00:30:27,020
That much more fortunate?

515
00:30:27,100 --> 00:30:30,440
Wealthy family, inherited
Daddy's shipping business,

516
00:30:30,520 --> 00:30:33,193
married rich... I
read your book.

517
00:30:33,273 --> 00:30:35,570
But there are things
you leave out of the book.

518
00:30:35,650 --> 00:30:38,282
Things you leave out because
if it got around polite society

519
00:30:38,362 --> 00:30:41,243
what you're capable
of when pushed,

520
00:30:41,323 --> 00:30:43,576
they might stop inviting
you to their dinner parties.

521
00:30:45,494 --> 00:30:49,874
All you know about me is
what I want you to know.

522
00:30:54,504 --> 00:30:56,259
MAN: Riders!

523
00:30:56,339 --> 00:30:57,677
Riders approaching!
[HORSE WHINNIES]

524
00:30:57,757 --> 00:30:59,593
MAN 2: Defend the governor!

525
00:31:02,345 --> 00:31:04,267
Captain, fall back and engage!

526
00:31:04,347 --> 00:31:05,892
Defend the left
flank! Fall back!

527
00:31:07,685 --> 00:31:09,729
[MEN SHOUTING]
[GRUNTING]

528
00:31:13,190 --> 00:31:15,443
[GUNFIRE]

529
00:31:16,819 --> 00:31:20,744
[SHOUTING CONTINUES]

530
00:31:20,824 --> 00:31:22,746
MAN: They're gaining, sir!

531
00:31:22,826 --> 00:31:25,916
[SHOUTS]
[GUNFIRE]

532
00:31:25,996 --> 00:31:27,918
MAN: Defend the governor!

533
00:31:27,998 --> 00:31:30,584
Faster! Don't spare the horses!

534
00:31:32,836 --> 00:31:33,712
Pistol!

535
00:31:35,340 --> 00:31:37,303
Hold your fire. Wait
till they're close.

536
00:31:37,383 --> 00:31:39,514
Sir! [HAMMER CLICKS]

537
00:31:39,594 --> 00:31:41,346
MAN: Pick your targets!

538
00:31:43,848 --> 00:31:44,811
[GUNFIRE]

539
00:31:44,891 --> 00:31:46,851
Ah! [WHINNIES]

540
00:31:48,227 --> 00:31:49,608
[MEN SHOUTING]

541
00:31:49,688 --> 00:31:52,778
Aah!

542
00:31:52,858 --> 00:31:54,780
[GUNFIRE CONTINUES]

543
00:31:54,860 --> 00:31:56,862
MAN: Yah! Yah!

544
00:32:04,704 --> 00:32:05,705
[GRUNTING]

545
00:32:11,544 --> 00:32:12,796
[YELPS]

546
00:32:44,371 --> 00:32:45,459
[HAMMER CLICKS]

547
00:32:45,539 --> 00:32:47,333
[GROANS] Aah!

548
00:33:06,812 --> 00:33:08,439
[MOANS]

549
00:33:09,648 --> 00:33:13,861
[GASPING]

550
00:33:21,619 --> 00:33:23,788
Ow.

551
00:33:33,591 --> 00:33:36,635
[GRUNTING]

552
00:33:37,928 --> 00:33:39,016
We need to move, now.

553
00:33:39,096 --> 00:33:42,520
Go! Go?

554
00:33:42,600 --> 00:33:43,521
Take the chest to the beach.

555
00:33:43,601 --> 00:33:45,482
We'll be right behind you.

556
00:33:45,562 --> 00:33:46,483
Right behind us?

557
00:33:46,563 --> 00:33:48,482
Yeah.

558
00:33:49,983 --> 00:33:51,989
[METAL CLATTERING]

559
00:33:52,069 --> 00:33:54,074
I thought you said you
and Nassau were through.

560
00:33:54,154 --> 00:33:55,492
[GRUNTS]

561
00:33:55,572 --> 00:33:57,494
Got worried you two'd
be lost without me.

562
00:33:57,574 --> 00:34:00,373
Glad to see I was
wrong about that.

563
00:34:00,453 --> 00:34:03,418
[GRUNTING]

564
00:34:03,498 --> 00:34:07,422
And Teach? How has he
taken your change of heart?

565
00:34:07,502 --> 00:34:08,840
Couldn't say.

566
00:34:08,920 --> 00:34:11,634
If you see him, I suppose
you could ask him.

567
00:34:11,714 --> 00:34:12,924
MAN: Yah!

568
00:34:19,890 --> 00:34:21,683
[CHAINS RATTLE]

569
00:34:25,646 --> 00:34:27,523
[GROANS]

570
00:34:32,112 --> 00:34:33,193
[HORSE WHINNIES]

571
00:34:33,342 --> 00:34:34,364
Look.

572
00:34:39,953 --> 00:34:40,874
Can you ride with him?

573
00:34:40,954 --> 00:34:41,871
Yeah.

574
00:34:49,004 --> 00:34:50,589
[GASPS] Go. Go!

575
00:35:00,225 --> 00:35:02,939
[VANE GROANS] Oh, God.

576
00:35:03,019 --> 00:35:04,896
[GRUNTS]

577
00:35:06,940 --> 00:35:08,442
Go!

578
00:35:12,028 --> 00:35:12,905
Go!

579
00:35:14,448 --> 00:35:16,537
Go! Go!

580
00:35:16,617 --> 00:35:18,536
Come on! Yah!

581
00:35:21,122 --> 00:35:22,001
[GUNSHOT]

582
00:35:22,081 --> 00:35:23,878
[PANTING]

583
00:35:23,958 --> 00:35:27,087
[GRUNTING]
[YELLS]

584
00:35:46,608 --> 00:35:48,943
[GRUNTING]

585
00:35:53,948 --> 00:35:57,036
[MEN SHOUTING]

586
00:36:00,247 --> 00:36:03,170
[GRUNTS]

587
00:36:03,250 --> 00:36:05,214
Put him down!

588
00:36:05,294 --> 00:36:06,924
MAN: Search for tracks!
Search the area! Hold him!

589
00:36:07,004 --> 00:36:08,717
MAN 2: See which way they went!

590
00:36:08,797 --> 00:36:12,097
[MEN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

591
00:36:12,177 --> 00:36:13,557
[VANE GRUNTS]

592
00:36:13,637 --> 00:36:17,057
[SILVER APPROACHING]

593
00:36:31,822 --> 00:36:33,866
Thank you.

594
00:36:38,120 --> 00:36:40,127
I've known him since
we were children...

595
00:36:40,207 --> 00:36:46,091
suffered illness
and loss by his side.

596
00:36:46,171 --> 00:36:48,760
Watched him give his loyalty,

597
00:36:48,840 --> 00:36:53,887
his sacrifice and his
love to my mother, to me.

598
00:36:57,976 --> 00:37:00,106
So you can just imagine
what that was like,

599
00:37:00,186 --> 00:37:04,736
asking him to accept
what was done to him

600
00:37:04,816 --> 00:37:07,739
at the hands of men
who look so very much

601
00:37:07,819 --> 00:37:12,032
like those he watched murder
his parents when he was a boy.

602
00:37:13,200 --> 00:37:15,748
You can imagine
how tempted I was

603
00:37:15,828 --> 00:37:17,208
to take that knife
and put it in his hand

604
00:37:17,288 --> 00:37:19,039
and let him use
it to his liking.

605
00:37:21,834 --> 00:37:25,175
You can imagine
the restraint it took

606
00:37:25,255 --> 00:37:28,008
for me not to let
my people loose.

607
00:37:36,182 --> 00:37:38,060
But where does that leave us?

608
00:37:40,813 --> 00:37:44,570
So I will fight this
thing rising up in me

609
00:37:44,650 --> 00:37:48,199
eager to see more
blood spilled today,

610
00:37:48,279 --> 00:37:53,205
and I will serve them
by minding their future

611
00:37:53,285 --> 00:37:55,582
and doing the hard thing

612
00:37:55,662 --> 00:37:59,583
that will lead to the
outcome desired by all of us.

613
00:38:03,295 --> 00:38:05,047
This will not happen again.

614
00:38:15,642 --> 00:38:17,897
It is over, then.

615
00:38:17,977 --> 00:38:19,145
We move forward.

616
00:38:23,317 --> 00:38:25,030
You have my word.

617
00:38:25,110 --> 00:38:28,322
[NO AUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

618
00:38:35,830 --> 00:38:39,042
[NO AUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

619
00:38:47,801 --> 00:38:51,222
Not a fucking word
about it, understand?

620
00:38:56,143 --> 00:38:58,854
[MOANING FAINTLY]

621
00:39:00,981 --> 00:39:05,741
MAN: Sails! Due
west! Headed this way!

622
00:39:05,821 --> 00:39:08,201
I thought you said that no
one could see us from here.

623
00:39:08,281 --> 00:39:10,912
They can't.

624
00:39:10,992 --> 00:39:13,412
[MEN CHATTERING]

625
00:39:20,461 --> 00:39:22,383
Get us underway.

626
00:39:22,463 --> 00:39:24,344
Back to the coast to
retrieve the shore party.

627
00:39:24,424 --> 00:39:26,346
But there's been no signal
yet from the shore party.

628
00:39:26,426 --> 00:39:30,141
That ship will be upon us
in two hours, maybe less.

629
00:39:30,221 --> 00:39:32,018
Get us underway.

630
00:39:32,098 --> 00:39:33,394
Make ready the launches!

631
00:39:33,474 --> 00:39:34,938
Lower the courses.

632
00:39:35,018 --> 00:39:36,940
[MEN SHOUTING]

633
00:39:37,020 --> 00:39:38,150
MAN: Lower the courses!

634
00:39:38,230 --> 00:39:41,191
♪

635
00:39:46,155 --> 00:39:48,202
I see you.

636
00:39:48,282 --> 00:39:50,080
Set a course to intercept her.

637
00:39:50,160 --> 00:39:51,206
Bring us port!

638
00:39:51,286 --> 00:39:52,871
MAN: Bring us to port!

639
00:39:55,832 --> 00:39:58,213
[MAN COUGHING]

640
00:39:58,293 --> 00:40:03,386
[MEN COUGHING]

641
00:40:03,466 --> 00:40:05,930
Six more of them
have fallen ill.

642
00:40:06,010 --> 00:40:08,224
There's now a total
of 14 reported cases.

643
00:40:08,304 --> 00:40:09,767
Are any of them mortal?

644
00:40:09,847 --> 00:40:13,729
Not yet, but our
forces are dwindling,

645
00:40:13,809 --> 00:40:17,066
and it will get worse
before it gets better.

646
00:40:17,146 --> 00:40:18,360
Meanwhile, Flint is
out there somewhere

647
00:40:18,440 --> 00:40:21,071
committed to waging
war against us.

648
00:40:21,151 --> 00:40:22,739
And soon news
will return to Nassau

649
00:40:22,819 --> 00:40:24,074
as to whether
Rackham and his money

650
00:40:24,154 --> 00:40:26,201
are on their way to Havana.

651
00:40:26,281 --> 00:40:30,080
And if they aren't,
if you and I are right,

652
00:40:30,160 --> 00:40:33,209
if something happened and Hornigold's
cavalry weren't in time to stop it,

653
00:40:33,289 --> 00:40:37,251
then in addition to everything
else, we will be at war with Spain.

654
00:40:38,836 --> 00:40:40,091
If you and I were right

655
00:40:40,171 --> 00:40:41,926
and something went wrong
with the governor's caravan,

656
00:40:42,006 --> 00:40:46,055
I fear there is something even
more unsettling we are about to face.

657
00:40:46,135 --> 00:40:47,349
What is that?

658
00:40:47,429 --> 00:40:49,226
You and I will be
immune to this disease,

659
00:40:49,306 --> 00:40:52,729
for it will only attack those
unfamiliar to this place.

660
00:40:52,809 --> 00:40:55,899
You and I know Flint
and can fight him.

661
00:40:55,979 --> 00:40:57,734
You and I, though outmatched,

662
00:40:57,814 --> 00:41:00,404
at least know what Spain
is and can make best efforts

663
00:41:00,484 --> 00:41:02,907
to confront whatever
they may send our way.

664
00:41:02,987 --> 00:41:04,742
But there is nothing
more dangerous

665
00:41:04,822 --> 00:41:06,494
than the unfamiliar enemy.

666
00:41:06,574 --> 00:41:09,080
If the governor's
caravan was attacked,

667
00:41:09,160 --> 00:41:11,040
it means someone
knew where to find it.

668
00:41:11,120 --> 00:41:15,253
It means our secrets
are no longer ours.

669
00:41:15,333 --> 00:41:18,796
It means there is
a spy among us.

670
00:41:20,464 --> 00:41:22,341
[HORSE WHINNIES]
[MAN SHOUTING]

671
00:41:23,968 --> 00:41:27,513
[CROWD CHATTERING]

672
00:41:42,487 --> 00:41:45,244
Someone help him.

673
00:41:45,324 --> 00:41:46,492
Fetch Dr. Marcus.

674
00:41:52,915 --> 00:41:54,458
MAN: Please see to it!

675
00:42:17,932 --> 00:42:19,444
Where's Vane?

676
00:42:21,029 --> 00:42:24,118
The militia arrived
before he could get away.

677
00:42:24,198 --> 00:42:25,867
We had no choice but to run.

678
00:42:27,994 --> 00:42:29,204
Fuck.

679
00:42:32,166 --> 00:42:34,421
Take him and the cache back
to the ship and get out of here.

680
00:42:34,501 --> 00:42:36,423
BILLY: What?
You can't stay behind.

681
00:42:36,503 --> 00:42:38,133
I'll go find Vane.

682
00:42:38,213 --> 00:42:41,470
Once he's free, we'll find
our own way back to the camp.

683
00:42:41,550 --> 00:42:42,471
Captain...

684
00:42:42,551 --> 00:42:43,765
Charles Vane
swinging over Nassau

685
00:42:43,845 --> 00:42:45,976
is a statement we
cannot afford to be made.

686
00:42:46,056 --> 00:42:47,557
You cannot stay.

687
00:42:49,476 --> 00:42:51,565
We're about to get
the war you wanted

688
00:42:51,645 --> 00:42:54,401
and perhaps a credible path
towards something resembling victory,

689
00:42:54,481 --> 00:42:57,446
but the war is going
to follow that chest

690
00:42:57,526 --> 00:42:59,445
and you're the only one
of us who can marshal it.

691
00:43:01,155 --> 00:43:03,449
RACKHAM: He's right.

692
00:43:05,159 --> 00:43:06,414
He's right.

693
00:43:06,494 --> 00:43:08,541
If Charles knew we
were even contemplating

694
00:43:08,621 --> 00:43:12,504
jeopardizing the
grander effort to save him,

695
00:43:12,584 --> 00:43:14,127
he'd kill us all.

696
00:43:17,005 --> 00:43:18,552
Give me two men.

697
00:43:18,632 --> 00:43:20,592
I'll go back and
address the situation.

698
00:43:23,512 --> 00:43:24,433
How?

699
00:43:24,513 --> 00:43:25,475
By stirring resentment,

700
00:43:25,555 --> 00:43:27,020
finding sympathetic ears,

701
00:43:27,100 --> 00:43:29,397
reminding them that Charles
Vane was once the best of them...

702
00:43:29,477 --> 00:43:30,648
still is the best of them.

703
00:43:30,728 --> 00:43:33,526
My parents were agitators.

704
00:43:33,606 --> 00:43:35,069
If we are to win this war,

705
00:43:35,149 --> 00:43:36,362
that may be exactly
what we need.

706
00:43:36,442 --> 00:43:39,574
By the time I'm through,

707
00:43:39,654 --> 00:43:40,909
the governor won't
be able to hang Vane

708
00:43:40,989 --> 00:43:42,578
out of fear of
losing the street.

709
00:43:42,658 --> 00:43:46,412
[MEN SHOUTING]

710
00:43:48,122 --> 00:43:51,208
[CHATTERING]

711
00:43:53,669 --> 00:43:54,712
[SIGHS]

712
00:44:14,316 --> 00:44:15,526
Charles is here.

713
00:44:18,821 --> 00:44:22,658
It's a very small consolation
given what we lost today.

714
00:44:25,162 --> 00:44:27,250
But you had the foresight
to put Captain Hornigold

715
00:44:27,330 --> 00:44:29,252
in pursuit of Flint's ship.

716
00:44:29,332 --> 00:44:31,588
It's the only reason we
have any prayer at all

717
00:44:31,668 --> 00:44:35,297
of recovering the cache
and avoiding disaster.

718
00:44:37,340 --> 00:44:40,264
If Hornigold is unable
to capture Flint's ship,

719
00:44:40,344 --> 00:44:44,435
Flint is able to dictate

720
00:44:44,515 --> 00:44:47,563
the next chapter of this story.

721
00:44:47,643 --> 00:44:49,273
The choices we
will likely then face

722
00:44:49,353 --> 00:44:53,569
will be of the
most awful kind...

723
00:44:53,650 --> 00:44:57,616
the ones that promise only
bad outcomes in every direction.

724
00:44:57,696 --> 00:45:01,116
Eleanor, look at me.

725
00:45:11,085 --> 00:45:13,633
The challenges I see
ahead for both you and I

726
00:45:13,713 --> 00:45:15,215
are of the gravest sort.

727
00:45:17,509 --> 00:45:19,264
I need to know that
I can rely upon you

728
00:45:19,344 --> 00:45:20,598
to help me navigate through it.

729
00:45:20,678 --> 00:45:23,224
Of course you can.

730
00:45:25,518 --> 00:45:27,732
You understand...

731
00:45:27,812 --> 00:45:30,443
my concern about
calling you a partner,

732
00:45:30,523 --> 00:45:32,361
from the moment I first
walked into your cell in London,

733
00:45:32,441 --> 00:45:36,741
was whether you'd be able
to resist Nassau's temptation,

734
00:45:36,821 --> 00:45:40,120
the gravity of your
personal history

735
00:45:40,200 --> 00:45:42,289
urging you to
resume petty rivalries

736
00:45:42,369 --> 00:45:47,127
and repeat the costliest
of your mistakes,

737
00:45:47,207 --> 00:45:49,254
preventing you from ever
truly moving into the future

738
00:45:49,334 --> 00:45:51,423
I wanted to build here

739
00:45:51,503 --> 00:45:53,092
rather than gravitating
back into your past.

740
00:45:53,172 --> 00:45:56,262
And now...

741
00:45:56,342 --> 00:45:59,724
in the moment I
need you the most,

742
00:45:59,804 --> 00:46:04,270
need the best of you the most,

743
00:46:04,350 --> 00:46:05,730
I fear the temptation
you are feeling

744
00:46:05,810 --> 00:46:07,771
is about to be at its strongest.

745
00:46:09,815 --> 00:46:11,487
You're wrong. No, I'm not wro...

746
00:46:11,567 --> 00:46:15,616
[COUGHS]

747
00:46:15,696 --> 00:46:18,282
[COUGHS, INHALES]

748
00:46:21,327 --> 00:46:22,704
I am not wrong.

749
00:46:26,332 --> 00:46:31,424
That man sitting
in a cell in my fort

750
00:46:31,504 --> 00:46:33,426
is the embodiment of
that temptation for you.

751
00:46:33,506 --> 00:46:34,719
It is self-evident.

752
00:46:34,799 --> 00:46:39,099
Now, I am asking
whether you're able

753
00:46:39,179 --> 00:46:42,792
to see past the petty
and the personal

754
00:46:42,984 --> 00:46:44,730
to remain focused
on what is right now

755
00:46:44,810 --> 00:46:49,109
of vital importance
to both of our futures...

756
00:46:49,189 --> 00:46:50,779
to our very survival.

757
00:46:50,859 --> 00:46:54,241
If you have any regard for me,

758
00:46:54,321 --> 00:46:57,577
any respect at all,

759
00:46:57,657 --> 00:46:59,913
then I'm asking you
to tell me the truth

760
00:46:59,993 --> 00:47:02,412
about what you're
capable of right now.

761
00:47:09,337 --> 00:47:10,758
The moment you walked
into my cell in London,

762
00:47:10,838 --> 00:47:12,798
do you want to know
what I first thought?

763
00:47:16,010 --> 00:47:17,765
I wasn't thinking about
the charges against me.

764
00:47:17,845 --> 00:47:21,770
I wasn't thinking about a
reprieve from the noose.

765
00:47:21,850 --> 00:47:23,438
I wasn't thinking about piracy,

766
00:47:23,518 --> 00:47:25,774
nor pardons, nor Nassau.

767
00:47:25,854 --> 00:47:29,691
In that moment, I was consumed by
one thought and one thought only...

768
00:47:33,821 --> 00:47:36,619
...the idea that this
may be my opportunity

769
00:47:36,699 --> 00:47:40,748
to gain some measure of revenge
against my father's murderer,

770
00:47:40,828 --> 00:47:44,836
that I might play a role in
the execution of Charles Vane.

771
00:47:44,916 --> 00:47:48,924
I know you now. I trust you now.

772
00:47:49,004 --> 00:47:51,802
I'm devoted to you now.

773
00:47:51,882 --> 00:47:53,217
I love you now.

774
00:47:56,845 --> 00:47:59,935
So I will tell you
the absolute truth

775
00:48:00,015 --> 00:48:02,438
about how I'm going to react
when faced with the thing

776
00:48:02,518 --> 00:48:04,729
sitting in that
cell in your fort.

777
00:48:09,818 --> 00:48:11,444
I honestly don't know.

778
00:48:14,072 --> 00:48:15,573
[DOOR SLAMS]

779
00:48:17,033 --> 00:48:19,912
♪

